analysis:
- The strongest designs converge on the same structural template: (1) fast nondominated filtering, (2) cheap per-point proxy ranking (axis-aligned box volume ± few-weight scalarizations) to produce a small candidate shortlist, (3) greedy/CELF insertion using cached singleton HVs (and selective pairwise caching), and (4) a bounded deterministic local 1-for-1 swap pass. That template minimizes expensive pg.hypervolume calls and concentrates exact computation where it matters.
- High-performing variants emphasize deterministic, small shortlists proportional to k, stable tie-breaking, and reuse of precomputed data (ref-minus, singleton HVs, pairwise HVs when shortlist ≤ ~40). CELF lazy updates or greedy-with-incremental-hv reduce redundant recomputation versus naive per-candidate recompute loops.
- Efficiency wins come from vectorization (compute diffs/rect vols in bulk), timestamped lazy heaps (avoid full re-evaluation each round), and tight caps on swap iterations/HV budget so runtime scales predictably with k and shortlist size.
- Common avoidable overheads seen in weaker/less effective heuristics:
  - repeated creation of temporary arrays (frequent vstack/reshape) inside inner loops instead of maintaining a reusable buffer;
  - naive Python-level membership checks and O(N) scans (e.g., "if cand in selected_idx") inside hot loops;
  - unbounded per-candidate HV recomputations instead of lazy/timestamped gains or incremental updates;
  - overly large or poorly tuned shortlists that force many exact HV calls, or conversely overly aggressive HV-call budgets that force fallback heuristics and hurt quality;
  - unnecessary pairwise HV caching for large shortlists (cost > benefit).
- Quality-vs-cost tradeoffs are controlled by three levers across heuristics: shortlist size, HV-call budget, and swap-budget. The best heuristics balance these (moderate shortlist, cached singletons, tight swap cap). Variants that add many weight vectors or dense pairwise caching only help if HV calls remain bounded.
- Data-reuse checklist that separates strong from weak implementations: precompute ref - points once; cache singleton HVs; reuse pairwise HVs only when shortlist small; avoid reconstructing arrays each HV call; and prefer heap/CELF to avoid recomputing unchanged marginals.
